Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth American president in history.
The diploma, medal and check of $1.4 million will be awarded, among other things, for the exceptional effort to strengthen global diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The White House chief and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian metropolis in the morning and will have much to do.
First, he visited the Nobel Institute, where for the first time he would meet the five members of the committee that, in October, elected him between 172 people and 33 organizations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is planning a meeting with the king of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon the visit will culminate with a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive him, although the third to receive him in office.
The White House has already announced that, upon receiving the award, it will speak of the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid this issue, knowing that he is receiving the prize as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts increased further with the sending of additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
It is proposed to donate them for charitable purposes, but has not yet decided which organization in particular.
During their full program, the President and his wife will participate in a banquet to which, in addition to the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests will attend.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the prize.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not fully deserving of it.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
