USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom · Global Voices
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent pupil repeats in the Afghan question his predecessor's strategy, which he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only does the same text use the "as in Iraq" speech several times, but it also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A New Way Forward."
It was he himself, who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no talk of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, however objectively he left his successor a much more favourable initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will be repeated.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even in spite of the traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to be able to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he cheated on the general about 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama’s entire strategy seems his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years. Obama’s entire doctrine generated more questions than the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is implemented.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing the chief every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. Patriarchal tribal relations will remain behind him.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated by confusing relationships, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum objective of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is collided with his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon," will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of troop withdrawal is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are becoming less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphal withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each such solution will mean a dramatic setback to the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years to go before the presidential elections and that is why there is still a long time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
