A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in HIV 'streets'
Team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds to moderate the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some already accessible medicines.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, the life of patients can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of medicines that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the virus replication is not completely suppressed, the so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metallocarranes have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarrans are composed of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a different way from all the medicines used today, and so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work scientists find new, ‘improved’ compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarrans have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedron cages composed of the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon are joined by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A traitorous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, there is no division of the HIV virus and no mature and infectious corpuscles of the virus would be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
