A UN group outlines a plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, characterized so far by defiant positions and mutual recriminations, caught renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that foresees ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations carrying on their shoulders most of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and highlighted the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a time-consuming negotiation, with more than 100 world leaders coming to Copenhagen next week.
Prepared by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not speak of how much money rich countries would give the poor to face global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit to the global temperature rise that political strategists would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, Washington High Representative for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture."
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by 25 to 45 percent, compared to 1990 levels, while major developing countries would cut their emissions over the same period by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50-95% by 2050.
The European Union also stimulated talks on Friday, promising to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years, to help the poorest countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday presented the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated conversations last week.
U.S. Special Climate Envoy Todd Stern rejected claims calling for mandatory cuts in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The maneuver indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China, with regard to what Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make an agreement without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his remarks an hour after Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, claimed that America's top climate negotiator lacked "common sense," or was "very irresponsible" for having said earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically cope with global overheating.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, the fault lines have erupted both within the developing world, as well as between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States confronting their respective obligations, while poorer nations insist that the twenty-four most influential countries of the world are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the bravest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that the major powers are discussing who should pay for spending to limit greenhouse gases, even though vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in seeking to contain the major emitters responsible for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is developing, said Ulate, who also works as a regional climate change advisor for Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, even if most of the main participants said that the talks would produce at most a political agreement.
The Alliance of Small Island States (AOSIS), which has 43 members, prepared a proposal for a 24-page preliminary treaty early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who leads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push of small island nations has "put political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now unified and demand action from emerging economies such as China and India.
The talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the exceptional issues before the heads of government come to close a deal.
High-level officials, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, descended from the planes and ran into the halls of the Bella Center, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, so that they could delimit the claims that will be arbitrated over the next week.
The absolute disorder of the meeting (where every day 13,000 people enter and leave the convention center, the activists who play the guitar present night shows mocking the countries that they say are selling, and pass preliminary proposals from hand to hand instead of via mail), poses a challenge.
