Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of the collaborators adhering to "values" determined from above as before was to impose on consumers products designed by factory technicians.
By putting the customer at the centre of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquering markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are unrelated to customer preference factors is repeated regularly.
A demobilization of employees can lead to a deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R & D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "demands that all parties involved (...) have proactive behaviour and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a management revolution, which would be to put the collaborators at the center of the company's concerns as well as the client.
Internal opinion polls have a relative usefulness
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the management revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
In principle, because I could verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many turns, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
- Second, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology mechanistically.
They adopt, for intellectual comfort, the old behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media widely spread behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management stance, maladapted to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies means adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into any reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means to make part of their dreams, ambitions and projects a reality.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of the motivations of employees.
The studies showed that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilisation factors, business managers can control, anticipate and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "in the place".
In this way, they create a favorable ground for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
