The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa encuenae looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high running on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this would not have been something special.
But the Tawa findae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's Science magazine.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the Pangea supercontinent in the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we've found a dozen dinosaur bones in a day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a member of the Utah Museum of Natural History team.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected in total the remains of five specimens.
One finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn for example.
According to the current trend of opinion, dinosaurs first appeared approximately 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods among which are Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivoros (saurians with bird pelvis), to which they belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa findae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa’s skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also owned by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa also found the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the theropod with the oldest and most primitive airbags, comments Randall Irmis.
Because the related line of the posterior giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest known dinosaurs so far lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurians first emerged there.
Consequently, the three genealogical lineages separated at the beginning and spread from South America throughout all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a unique land mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say that the team found together with Tawa the remains of two other theropods not closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the science studio.
Naturally, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, comments Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while in other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to dominant Mesozoic terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of present-day crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Toward the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs expanded all over the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the limit of the Triassic towards the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a massive extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Success stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact slowed the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved into the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
