In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
Not only the mentally ill and drug addicts are the boundaries between imagination and reality fading.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unfetteredly surrender ourselves to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleeplike states during the vigil, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often regarded in the modern Western world as mad or drug addicted, or at least as maniac.
But such images and voices not only arise in the mentally ill or in the drug addicts.
The fault is our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to blur.
Oneirically modified alert states of consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, the visions of Hildegard von Bingen mysticism, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Charles Castañeda, the states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations can be referred to similar processes.
