In this world too conscious, imaginary experiences tend to be pathologicalized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as being a dream.
Oneiric hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that later cannot differentiate from being awake.
Oneiric conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis being fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische Lähmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of its own and imaginary that is disconnected from reality.
A form of situation bordering on sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an inexhaustible situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a saving action of the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several-day journeys after an operation of heart valves with heart transplant included, while his body was condemned to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places of other times: he saw himself prostrate in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
It was seen in the high Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed his hospital bed in the Alps with top snow and met a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in memories.
For Claussen, these interior trips are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, thus describing your experience.
On the contrary, memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intensive even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Every modification of the state of consciousness, sums up psychologist Kasten, "may lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
