Seventy-five per cent of working mothers have had problems working because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fecundity and career history of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey conducted between 9,737 women aged 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about it: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of partnering and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they do.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have a non-stable job, first start living together, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting their cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life path to obtain them, which has led them to postpone the union and arrival of the children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts much influence on motherhood, although less on the timing of the pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and when they have the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the older the age at which they marry and the first child.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at the average age of 25.1 and 32.1 respectively.
"Another division is also established among women according to their level of education.
While those who have elementary education marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those at middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado explains.
