Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As was the case with ABS anti-lock brakes and it will pass with ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already registered in all new passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a period of deficiency is fixed until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection although, because of its way of working, it can also help avoid many collisions by scope.
The emergency braking assistant does increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's stomping.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not reached the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with damage to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system becomes popular.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps you increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If you do not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
